{{DISPLAYTITLE:''Dos Bocas'' oil fire}}
The '''''Dos Bocas'' oil fire''' was a 1908 [[blowout (well drilling)|blowout]] and [[oil fire]] that took place in [[Veracruz, Veracruz|Veracruz, Mexico]]. The fire started after a blowout occurred, causing [[crude oil]] to make contact with the flames that powered the [[oil derrick]]. The fire continued from 4 July 1908 to 30 August 1908, when the oil deposit was burnt out. For the nearly two months that the fire burned, nearly {{convert|90000|oilbbl}} of oil flowed into the surrounding landscape each day. Ultimately, the ''Dos Bocas'' blowout (named for the two gaping black holes it left it the ground - "two mouths") ended up being one of the largest oil spills in the history of the oil industry.<ref>{{Cite book|title = An Environmental History of Latin America|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=p21VdbT7qAMC|publisher = Cambridge University Press|date = 2007-09-10|isbn = 9780521848534|language = en|first = Shawn William|last = Miller}}</ref> The two large craters formed in the ground around the oil well were caused by the pressure of the oilfield. It was impossible to stop the flow of oil because the well casing had been blown off during the gush.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|title = The Memory of Catastrophe|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=1T0BCw3tYRcC|publisher = Manchester University Press|date = 2004-09-04|isbn = 9780719063459|language = en|first = Peter|last = Gray|first2 = Kendrick|last2 = Oliver}}</ref>The heat exacerbated the difficulties workers faced when trying to stop the flow of oil. Temperatures were high which caused those working to put out the fire and contain the spill to be unable to go closer than a few hundred feet.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Oil and Revolution in Mexico|url = http://publishing.cdlib.org/ucpressebooks/view?docId=ft3q2nb28s&chunk.id=d0e1838&toc.depth=1&toc.id=0&brand=ucpress&query=bocas|website = publishing.cdlib.org|accessdate = 2015-09-15}}</ref> The oil coming out was a {{convert|200|ft|m|adj=mid|tall}} column and the fire burned at over {{convert|1000|°F}}. <ref>{{Cite book|title = Bulletin|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=ktpXAAAAYAAJ|date = 1914-01-01|language = en|first = Pan American|last = Union}}</ref> {{convert|27|km|spell=In|abbr=out}} away from the fire, town residents said that they were able to read a newspaper at night by the light of the flames.<ref name=":0" /> The cost of extinguishing the fire and capping the well was $3,000,000.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Showalter |first1=William Joseph |title="Mexico and Mexicans" |journal=The National Geographic Magazine |date=May 1914 |volume=25 |issue=5 |page=490}}</ref>

