'''Energy in Estonia''' describes [[World energy resources and consumption|energy]] and [[Electricity generation|electricity]] production, consumption and import in [[Estonia]].
Electricity production in Estonia is largely dependent on fossil fuels. In 2007, more than 90% of power was generated from [[oil shale in Estonia|oil shale]].<ref>Francu, Juraj; Harvie, Barbra; Laenen, Ben; Siirde, Andres; Veiderma, Mihkel [http://www.easac.org/fileadmin/PDF_s/reports_statements/Study.pdf A study on the EU oil shale industry viewed in the light of the Estonian experience. A report by EASAC to the Committee on Industry, Research and Energy of the European Parliament] European Academies Science Advisory Council. pp. 14–15; 45. May 2007</ref> The Estonian energy company [[Eesti Energia]] owns the largest [[oil shale]]-fuelled power plants in the world, [[Narva Power Plants]].<ref>[http://www.kirj.ee/public/oilshale/oil-2007-1-1.pdf "Oil Shale Energetics in Estonia] Liive, Sandor (2007) Oil Shale. A Scientific-echnical Journal (Estonian Academy Publishers) 24 (1): 1–4</ref>
