{{Infobox power transmission line | name = Masaka–Mutukula–Mwanza High Voltage Power Line | photo = | caption = | map = | country = [[Uganda]] & [[Tanzania]] | state = | province = | coordinates ={{coord|00|59|51|S|31|24|52|E|type:landmark_region:UG|display=inline}} | direction = North to South | start = Masaka, [[Uganda]] | through = [[Mutukula, Uganda|Mutukula]], [[Bukoba]] | finish = [[Mwanza]], [[Tanzania]] | par = | owner = [[Government of Uganda]] & [[Government of Tanzania]] | partners = [[East African Community]] | operator = [[Uganda Electricity Transmission Company Limited]] & [[Tanzania Electric Supply Company Limited]] | cable_manufacturer = | cable_installer = | cable_layer = | substation_manufacturer = | substation_installer = | contractors = | construction = TBD | expected = TBD | est = | decom = | type = | current_type = AC | length =582 | length_mi = | tower_no = | capacity = | AC_voltage = 220kV | DC_voltage = | poles_no = | circuits_no = 2 }}
The '''Masaka–Mutukula–Mwanza High Voltage Power Line''' is a proposed [[high voltage]] electricity power line, connecting the high voltage [[Electrical substation|substation]] at [[Masaka]], in [[Masaka District]], in the [[Central Region, Uganda|Central Region]] of [[Uganda]], to another high voltage substation at [[Mwanza]], in [[Mwanza Region]], in the [[Republic of Tanzania]].<ref name="One">{{cite web| date=5 January 2018 |format=PDF | accessdate=5 January 2018 |url=https://www.newvision.co.ug/digital_assets/a1cd019e-418b-4297-8260-ba308df58da0/32-ERA-Full-pg.pdf | location=Kampala | publisher=[[Electricity Regulatory Authority]] (ERA) | author=ERA | title=Regional Power Transmission Projects}}</ref>
==Location== The power line starts at the [[Uganda Electricity Transmission Company Limited]] (UETCL) 220kV substation in Masaka. The line travels in a general southwesterly direction to [[Mutukula, Uganda|Mutukula]], at the international border with Tanzania. From Mutukula, the power line continues in a general southeasterly direction to [[Bukoba]], on the western shores of [[Lake Victoria]]. From Bukoba, the line loops around the lake, and continues eastwards to end at [[Mwanza]]. The Ugandan portion of the power line measures {{convert|82|km|0}}.<ref name="Two">{{cite web| url=http://www.uetcl.com/index.php/site-administrator/projects-at-feasibility-study | title=Projects Under Feasibility Study | accessdate=5 January 2018 | location=Kampala| date=5 January 2018 | publisher=[[Uganda Electricity Transmission Company Limited]] (UETCL) | author=UETCL}}</ref> The distance travelled by the power line in Tanzania is approximately {{convert|500|km|0}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://distancecalculator.globefeed.com/Tanzania_Distance_Result.asp?fromplace=Mutukula%2C%20Kagera%20Region%2C%20Tanzania&toplace=Mwanza%2C%20Mwanza%20Region%2C%20Tanzania&dt1=ChIJ4VEv6An32RkR9d1qWvXy3OY&dt2=ChIJkfuMScZkzhkRHaUjfwomKXU | title=Distance between Mutukula, Kagera Region, Tanzania and Mwanza, Mwanza Region, Tanzania |accessdate=5 January 2017 |last=Globefeed.com |publisher=Globefeed.com |date=5 January 2017}}</ref>
==Overview== This power line is intended to enable Uganda and Tanzania to share electric energy. As part of the energy-sharing protocols of the [[East African Community]], and [[Nile Basin Initiative]], Uganda plans to increase energy sales to Tanzania, when [[Karuma Hydroelectric Power Station]] comes online in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=7 January 2018| date=4 October 2017|first=and Nelson Wesonga |last=Stephen Otage |url=http://www.monitor.co.ug/News/National/Uganda-to-export-electricity-to-South-Sudan--DR-Congo/688334-4123918-np6qx4z/index.html |title=Uganda to export electricity to South Sudan, DR Congo | newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=How River Nile is powering 10 nations | url=https://www.newvision.co.ug/new_vision/news/1464905/river-nile-powering-nations |accessdate=7 January 2018 |first=Pascal |last=Kwesiga |date=2 November 2017 |newspaper=[[New Vision (newspaper)|New Vision]]}}</ref> The construction of this high voltage power line has been planned as far back as 2011.<ref>{{cite web| date=1 December 2011 |last=Nyakato |first=Joyce | url=https://www.newvision.co.ug/new_vision/news/1003905/uetcl-buys-markets-power-uetcl-10th-anniversaary-supplement | title=UETCL buys and markets power–UETCL 10th Anniversary supplement | accessdate=7 January 2018 |newspaper=[[New Vision (newspaper)|New Vision]]}}</ref>
==Construction== As of January 2018, the feasibility study, environmental impact assessment and population resettlement plans were complete. Plans to construct the power line were underway, under the auspices of the East African Community.<ref name="Two"/>
